    <p>
      The following proposition provides answers for Problems (3) and (4).
    </p>
    <p>
      <em><xref ref="prop_lincomb"></xref></em>.
      For all natural numbers <m>n</m> with <m>n \geq 8</m>,
      there exist non-negative integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> such that <m>n = 3x + 5y</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        (by mathematical induction) Let <m>\mathbb{Z}^* = \left\{ {x \in \mathbb{Z}\left. \right| x \geq 0} \right\}</m>,
        and for each natural number <m>n</m>,
        let <m>P\left( n \right)</m> be,
        <q>there exist <m>x,
        y \in \mathbb{Z}^*</m> such that <m>n = 3x + 5y</m>.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Basis Step</em>: Using the table above,
        we see that <m>P\left( 8 \right)</m>,
        <m>P\left( 9 \right)</m>, and <m>P\left( {10} \right)</m> are true.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Inductive Step</em>: Let
        <m>k \in \mathbb{N}</m> with <m>k \geq 10</m>.
        Assume that <m>P\left( 8 \right)</m>,
        <m>P\left( 9 \right)</m>, <ellipsis/> , <m>P\left( k \right)</m> are true.
        Now, notice that
        <me>
          k + 1 = 3 + \left( {k - 2} \right)
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Since <m>k \geq 10</m>, we can conclude that
        <m>k - 2 \geq 8</m> and hence <m>P\left( {k - 2} \right)</m> is true.
        Therefore, there exist non-negative integers <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> such that <m>k - 2 = \left( {3u + 5v} \right)</m>.
        Using this equation, we see that
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}k + 1 \amp = 3  + \left( {3u + 5v} \right) \\ \amp = 3\left( {1 + u} \right) + 5v. \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
      <p>
        Hence, we can conclude that <m>P\left( {k + 1} \right)</m> is true.
        This proves that if <m>P\left( 8 \right)</m>, <m>P\left( 9 \right)</m>,
        <ellipsis/> , <m>P\left( k \right)</m> are true,
        then <m>P\left( {k + 1} \right)</m> is true.
        Hence, by the Second Principle of Mathematical Induction,
        for all natural numbers <m>n</m> with <m>n \geq 8</m>,
        there exist nonnegative integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> such that <m>n = 3x + 5y</m>.
      </p>
    </proof>
